// Author: Daniel J. Dillberg
// =====================================================
// DVSM — DETERMINSITIC VECTOR STATE MACHINE
// GITHUB README (SWIFT-EMBEDDED SPECIFICATION)
// =====================================================
//
// PROJECT NAME:
// DVSM v∞ — Reality-Stable Deterministic Execution System
//
// AUTHOR:
// Daniel J. Dillberg
//
// STATUS:
// Research / Architectural Specification / High-Assurance System Design
//
// PRIMARY PURPOSE:
// DVSM is a causally-closed deterministic execution architecture
// designed to guarantee reproducible state transitions across
// heterogeneous hardware while preserving strict separation of:
//   - Truth (Kernel)
//   - Interpretation (Observer)
//   - Ingestion (Provenance Compiler)
//   - Execution (Node Runtime)
//   - Consistency (Distributed Contract)
//   - Formal Verification (Impossibility Layer)
//
// =====================================================
// 🧠 SYSTEM SUMMARY
// =====================================================
//
// DVSM is not a traditional application framework.
//
// It is a deterministic state machine that:
//
// - Converts input flux into irreversible state transitions
// - Ensures identical inputs produce identical kernel traces
// - Separates computation from observation and interpretation
// - Eliminates timing, IO, and runtime dependency from truth logic
//
// The system is designed around a single invariant:
//
//     "Reality is the hash of state transitions, not time."
//
// =====================================================
// 🧱 ARCHITECTURE OVERVIEW
// =====================================================
//
// L1 — Kernel (Truth Engine)
// -------------------------------------
// The kernel is a pure deterministic transition function.
//
//   Input: DVSMFixedVector (validated flux)
//   Output: DVSMCommitResult (hash + sequence)
//
// Properties:
// - No IO
// - No randomness
// - No time dependency
// - Constant-time execution (O(1))
//
// -------------------------------------
//
// L2 — Observer (Interpretation Layer)
// -------------------------------------
// Converts kernel outputs into semantic meaning.
//
// Responsibilities:
// - Spectral analysis (optional)
// - Audit logging (async)
// - Geometry reconstruction
// - Ghost-state forecasting (non-authoritative)
//
// Constraint:
// NEVER influences kernel state.
//
// -------------------------------------
//
// L2.5 — Spectral Observer (Noise Deconstruction)
// -------------------------------------
// Diagnostic-only subsystem for signal classification.
//
// Functions:
// - FFT-based or deterministic spectral fingerprinting
// - Noise classification (stable, thermal, adversarial, drift)
// - EMA smoothing for interpretive stability
//
// Constraint:
// Observational ONLY — no causal influence.
//
// -------------------------------------
//
// L3 — SDK (Provenance Compiler)
// -------------------------------------
// Transforms raw external input into validated deterministic intent.
//
// Responsibilities:
// - Cryptographic signing (Curve25519)
// - Normalization of flux into fixed representation
// - Version pinning of normalization logic
// - Causal nonce generation (deterministic identity binding)
//
// Constraint:
// Must fully sanitize untrusted input BEFORE kernel exposure.
//
// -------------------------------------
//
// L4 — Node (Execution Substrate)
// -------------------------------------
// Physical runtime layer controlling:
//
// - Tick clock (deterministic pulse cadence)
// - Core affinity (kernel isolation)
// - Ingress buffer (MRW policy)
// - Observer dispatch (async fan-out)
//
// Constraint:
// Kernel remains isolated from OS variability.
//
// -------------------------------------
//
// L5 — Causal Consistency Layer
// -------------------------------------
// Ensures distributed equivalence across DVSM nodes.
//
// Responsibilities:
// - Merkle root validation
// - Replay consistency
// - Sequence integrity checks
//
// Constraint:
// No mutation authority — only verification.
//
// -------------------------------------
//
// L6 — Formal Verification Layer
// -------------------------------------
// Defines system-wide impossibility conditions.
//
// Guarantees:
// - No divergence under identical input
// - No post-validation mutation
// - No observer influence on kernel
// - No causal reordering allowed
//
// DVSM is treated as a mathematically constrained system.
//
// =====================================================
// ⚙️ CORE EXECUTION MODEL
// =====================================================
//
// DVSM operates on a "Pulse" model:
//
//     Pulse(t):
//         1. Ingest validated intent
//         2. Apply deterministic law (DVSMLaw)
//         3. Commit state transition
//         4. Emit cryptographic hash
//         5. Dispatch observers asynchronously
//
// Key property:
// Time is not an input — sequence is.
//
// =====================================================
// 🔐 DETECTION MODEL (BOILERPLATE EXAMPLE)
// =====================================================
//
// Example kernel flow:
//
// let kernel = DVSMKernel(initial: DVSMBitBlock())
//
// let result = kernel.pulse(validatedFlux)
//
// print(result.hash)
//
// This produces:
// - Deterministic state transition
// - Sequence increment
// - Cryptographic hash of new state
//
// No randomness exists in this process.
//
// =====================================================
// 🧪 OBSERVATION PIPELINE (BOILERPLATE)
// =====================================================
//
// let observer = DVMSpectralObserver()
//
// let result = observer.inspect(
//     samples: signalBuffer,
//     persistence: persistenceValue
// )
//
// Result includes:
// - spectralEnergy (normalized or fingerprinted)
// - classification (stable / noise / adversarial / drift)
//
// IMPORTANT:
// This does NOT affect kernel state.
//
// =====================================================
// 🌐 DISTRIBUTED BEHAVIOR
// =====================================================
//
// Across multiple nodes:
//
// - Each node runs identical kernel logic
// - State equivalence is validated via Merkle roots
// - Divergence is treated as invalid system behavior
//
// DVSM does NOT rely on consensus.
// It relies on deterministic replay equivalence.
//
// =====================================================
// ⚠️ DESIGN CONSTRAINTS
// =====================================================
//
// The following are strictly forbidden inside L1:
//
// - Floating-time dependency
// - IO operations
// - Async mutation
// - Non-deterministic math
// - Observer feedback loops
//
// Observers MUST NEVER:
// - modify flux
// - influence kernel execution
// - affect sequence ordering
//
// =====================================================
// 🚀 USE CASES
// =====================================================
//
// DVSM is applicable to:
//
// - High-integrity distributed systems
// - Aerospace sensor fusion
// - Financial settlement engines
// - Swarm robotics coordination
// - Deterministic simulation engines
//
// =====================================================
// 🧭 DESIGN PHILOSOPHY
// =====================================================
//
// DVSM is built on one principle:
//
//     "If two systems see the same input, they must become
//      the same system state — regardless of hardware."
//
// Everything else is enforcement.
//
// =====================================================
